fields.history_note:
Notes by W.A.Thorpe c1959:
W.179-1910

Casket.  Oak carcase covered in boiled leather with tooled decoration on a stippled ground, fitted with ironwork hinges, mounts and locks; traces of gilding on the iron.  

Rectangular plan (ichnography).  Five hinges, the upper members travelling forwards in the form shaped and buttoned rides on dentated bands the lower members travelling in similar form backwards, and plain and flat beneath.  Four similar transverse buttoned sides, plain and flat beneath.

On the lid, an ornamental ironwork loop-handle secured on the second and fourth sides by dragon heads, and bearing twice, between three buds [?], the fusil [light musket] on a flint, adopted, with allusion to the motto ANTE FERIT QUAM FLAMMA MICET, as his device, by Philip "the Good" (b.Dijon 1396, d. Bruges 1467), Duke of Burgundy.  In the fore-corners, pointing to the corner, shields of arms, long void, and in the same panels beyond them, legends in scrolls in Gothic letter, not certainly legible.  In the two centre panels of the lid, a design of leaves and foliage.

Round the sides of the lid, a band, including Gothic arcading, below a looped parapet.

On the front, two shaped locks and corresponding hasps, released by the movement of a castellated columnar catch between them.  On the leather ground, scrolled foliage.

In the three panels (also between rides) at either end, sprays of foliage pendent from ornamental versions of the fusil (without flint) approximating the letter B for Burgundy.  Similar rear panels. 

Rides flat below.  Interior not lined; traces of (later?) paper lining on lid.

BURGUNDIAN OR FLEMISH; mid 15th century.


General Remarks

Castellated style marked.  Fusil device familiar in the Collar of the order of the Knights of the Golden Fleece instituted by Philip the Good in 1429, and in the insignia and ornament of individual Knights of that Order.  

CASKET.  Beechwood carcase covered in boiled leather, with tooled, gilt, and coloured decoration.  Two brass hinge-rides and one brass hasp-ride.  Iron lockplate.  Brass toes.

Rectangular form with coved lid.  On the lid, sides, front, and rear, geometric and linear patterns enclosing panels containing traces of confronting pairs in gilding and colour.  On each end, panels containing a recumbent doe [?] among flowers and foliage.  

Floreated hinge-rides and hasp-ride, the hasp-ride travelling below a brass loop-handle.  Square over lock-plate with trefoil corners.  Covered underside with diamond diaper of double lines.

 A brass loop-handle.  Square iron lock-plate with trefoil corners.  Interior lined later with light-blue linen; on lid a cross in salmon-coloured silk outlined in gold thread.

FRENCH OR FLEMISH' 16th century.

No negatives.

Bought out of the Funds of the Bequest of Captain Henry Boyles Muarry.

BOX. Beechwood carcase covered with boiled leather with tooled decoration.  Iron mounts.  

Rectangular ichnography with slightly coved lid.  Five iron hinges, the upper sides travelling forward over the lid and terminating on the front, the central side terminating in a hinged hasp filling into a plated lock' and the lower sides travelling across the underside and terminating on the front.  Interior and embushment lined with plain leather, formerly throughout.
